# Day5 - Log Analysis

## What Are Logs?
Logs are records of everything that happens on a system.
Every login, every command, every connection — the system writes it down.

Think of logs like a security camera recording:
- Someone logs in → recorded
- A file is opened → recorded
- A connection is made → recorded
- A command is run → recorded

SOC analysts read these recordings to find suspicious activity.

---

## Where Are Logs Stored in Linux?
```
/var/log/
```

View all log files:
```bash
ls /var/log/
```

---

## Most Important Log Files For SOC

| Log File | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `auth.log` | Login attempts, SSH access, sudo commands |
| `syslog` | General system activity |
| `kern.log` | Linux kernel messages |
| `ufw.log` | Firewall activity — blocked/allowed connections |
| `apache2/` | Web server access and errors |
| `dpkg.log` | Software installation history |
| `btmp` | Failed login attempts |
| `wtmp` | Successful login history |

---

## Log Rotation
Linux automatically archives old logs:
```
auth.log      ← current
auth.log.1    ← last week
auth.log.2.gz ← older (compressed)
```

Always check multiple log files during investigation — not just the current one.

---

## Understanding The Log Format

Every line follows this structure:
```
DATE & TIME        HOSTNAME      SERVICE      MESSAGE
2026-04-01T13:50   Ubuntu-2204   sshd[3257]   Accepted password for albert
```

| Part | Meaning |
|---|---|
| Date & Time | When it happened |
| Hostname | Which machine |
| Service | Which service reported it |
| Message | What actually happened |

