## Auth.log — Login Activity

### Key Commands

Find failed login attempts:
```bash
sudo grep -a "Failed password" /var/log/auth.log
```

Find successful logins:
```bash
sudo grep -a "Accepted password" /var/log/auth.log
```

Find all SSH activity:
```bash
sudo grep -a "sshd" /var/log/auth.log
```

Check older logs:
```bash
sudo grep -a "Failed password" /var/log/auth.log.1
```

Count failed attempts per IP:
```bash
sudo grep -a "Failed password" /var/log/auth.log | awk '{print $11}' | sort | uniq -c | sort -rn
```

### Why -a Flag?
`-a` tells grep to treat the file as plain text even if it contains binary data.
Always use `-a` when reading system logs to avoid "binary file matches" warning.

