## Brute Force Attack Pattern

A brute force attack in auth.log looks like this:
```
2026-04-01T03:12:01  sshd  Failed password for root from 185.234.x.x port 22
2026-04-01T03:12:02  sshd  Failed password for root from 185.234.x.x port 22
2026-04-01T03:12:03  sshd  Failed password for root from 185.234.x.x port 22
2026-04-01T03:12:04  sshd  Failed password for root from 185.234.x.x port 22
```

### Four Red Flags To Look For

| Red Flag | Why Suspicious |
|---|---|
| Same IP repeating | One source hammering your machine |
| Targeting root account | Attacker wants highest privilege |
| Seconds apart | Automated tool — not a human typing |
| Unusual time (3am) | Nobody should be logging in at 3am |

---

## Golden Rule After Finding Brute Force

Always check if any attempt succeeded BEFORE doing anything else:
```bash
sudo grep -a "Accepted password" /var/log/auth.log | grep "185.234.x.x"
```

- If result found → active breach → emergency escalation
- If no result → all blocked → escalate to block IP permanently

Never close a brute force case without checking all three:
1. Did any attempt succeed?
2. Is the attack still ongoing?
3. Are there other IPs doing the same thing?

