## UFW Log — Firewall Activity

UFW = Uncomplicated Firewall — Ubuntu's built in firewall.
Records every connection blocked or allowed.

### Key Command
```bash
sudo tail -30 /var/log/ufw.log
```

### UFW Log Format
```
[UFW BLOCK] IN=enp0s3 SRC=185.234.x.x DST=192.168.1.214 PROTO=TCP DPT=22
```

| Field | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `UFW BLOCK` | Firewall blocked this connection |
| `IN=enp0s3` | Traffic came through this interface |
| `SRC=` | Where traffic came FROM |
| `DST=` | Where traffic was going TO |
| `PROTO=` | Protocol used (TCP/UDP) |
| `DPT=` | Destination port targeted |

### Key Fields To Focus On

| Field | What To Check |
|---|---|
| `SRC=` | Internal or external IP? Known or unknown? |
| `DST=` | What was targeted? |
| `DPT=` | What port was targeted? |
| Frequency | How many times? How fast? |

---

## Normal vs Suspicious UFW Traffic

| Normal Traffic | Suspicious Traffic |
|---|---|
| Internal IPs (192.168.x.x) | External IPs (185.x.x.x) |
| Multicast destinations (224.x.x.x) | Your machine as destination |
| IGMP protocol | TCP targeting specific ports |
| Normal intervals | Rapid repeated attempts |

