## The O-M-C Method

Use this framework for every log finding:

```
O → What exactly do I see in the log?
M → What does this tell me?
C → What action do I take next?
```

### Example — Brute Force Attack
```
O → External IP 45.227.x.x blocked by firewall 200 times
    in 5 minutes targeting port 22 (SSH)

M → Active brute force attack against SSH
    Automated tool — too fast for human typing
    External unknown IP — not from our network

C → Check if any attempt succeeded first
    sudo grep -a "Accepted password" /var/log/auth.log | grep "45.227"
    If succeeded → active breach → emergency escalation
    If all blocked → escalate to senior analyst to permanently block IP
```

---

## Incident Report — What To Include When Escalating

Never just say "something suspicious happened."
Always provide full details:

```
1. What you found     → 200 blocked SSH attempts
2. Source IP          → 45.227.x.x
3. Time range         → 5 minutes
4. Port targeted      → 22 (SSH)
5. Your check result  → No successful logins found
6. Your recommendation → Block IP at firewall permanently
```

---

## CRON Jobs — Normal Activity

You will see many lines like this in auth.log:
```
CRON[2398]: session opened for user root
CRON[2398]: session closed for user root
```

CRON = scheduled automatic tasks.
Opens and closes immediately = completely normal. ✅
Do not investigate these unless the timing or user is unexpected.

---

## Common Mistakes

- ❌ Blocking suspicious IP without checking if attack succeeded first
- ❌ Reading only current log — always check auth.log.1 as well
- ❌ Panicking over grep results that are actually your own commands
- ❌ Ignoring logins from different source IPs
- ❌ Closing brute force cases without verifying all attempts failed
- ❌ Escalating without full incident details

